<HEAD>For Release, Wednesday, Nov. 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, Nov. 30, the 335th day of 1988. There are 31
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1835, Samuel Langhorne Clemens _ better known as Mark Twain,
the author of such classics as ``Tom Sawyer'' and ``Adventures of
Huckleberry Finn'' _ was born in Florida, Mo.
   On this date:
   In 1782, the United States and Britain signed preliminary peace
articles in Paris, ending the Revolutionary War.
   In 1804, the first U.S. Supreme Court justice to be impeached,
Samuel Chase, went on trial in Washington. (He was acquitted.)
   In 1874, British statesman Sir Winston Churchill was born at
Blenheim Palace.
   In 1900, Irish author Oscar Wilde died in Paris.
   In 1939, the Soviet Union invaded Finland.
   In 1949, the Chinese Communists captured Chungking.
   In 1954, Elizabeth Hodges of Sylacauga, Ala., was injured when an
8{-pound meteorite crashed through the roof of her house.
   In 1962, U Thant of Burma was elected Secretary-General of the
United Nations, succeeding the late Dag Hammarskjold.
   In 1967, Julie Nixon and David Eisenhower announced their
engagement.
   In 1979, during a pilgrimage in Turkey, Pope John Paul II
participated in an Orthodox Mass honoring the feast day of Saint
Andrew, becoming the first pontiff in several centuries to attend.
   In 1981, the United States and the Soviet Union opened
negotiations in Geneva aimed at reducing nuclear weapons in Europe.
   Ten years ago: While angry demonstrators chanted outside, former
President Richard M. Nixon received a generally warm reception from
the Oxford Union in England, where he talked about foreign affairs
and fielded questions from the audience.
   Five years ago: Robert Sullivan, convicted of the 1973 robbery
and murder of Donald Schmidt, an assistant restaurant manager, was
executed in Florida's electric chair despite an appeal from Pope
John Paul II to spare his life.
   One year ago: In an interview broadcast by NBC, Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev acknowledged that his country was engaged in
Star Wars-related research, but said there were no plans to build a
space-based system against nuclear attack.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Virginia Mayo is 68. Actor Efrem
Zimbalist Jr. is 65. Former New York Rep. Shirley Chisholm is 64.
Actor Richard Crenna is 61. Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev., is 60. TV
host-producer Dick Clark is 59. Convicted Watergate defendant G.
Gordon Liddy is 58. Political activist Abbie Hoffman is 52.
Playwright David Mamet is 41. Singer Billy Idol is 33.
   Thought for Today: ``Keep away from people who try to belittle
your ambitions. Small people always do that, but the really great
make you feel that you, too, can become great.'' _ Mark Twain
(1835-1910).
</TEXT>
